  <body>
    <segment id="1" parent="35" relname="span">The traditional Korean home was divided into male and female apartments. </segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="30" relname="span">
The master of the house had a study and drawing room where guests were received.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="2" relname="elaboration">  
Typical furniture included reading and writing tables, document chests and cupboards 
with several display shelves above them.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="33" relname="span">  
In the women&apos;s quarters the business of running the household took place.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="31" relname="span">  
Much of the furniture was made up of chests arranged vertically in matching pairs, </segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="5" relname="elaboration">
or even three pieces one on top of the other.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="32" relname="span">
Female guests were entertained in these rooms,</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="7" relname="elaboration"> 
which often had beautifully crafted wooden toilet boxes with fold-away mirrors and sewing boxes, and folding screens, painted with birds and flowers.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="40" relname="span">

Chests were used for the storage of clothes,</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration"> 
usually folded rather than hung, and bedding.</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="43" relname="span">
The type of chest known as bandaji is rectangular, 
with the upper half of the front hinged at the base and opening downwards.</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="12" relname="condition">
If it was to be used for storing books or scrolls </segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="12" relname="conjunction">
it had small drawers and cupboards inside </segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="12" relname="conjunction">
and was kept in the male quarters.</segment>
    <segment id="16" parent="42" relname="span">  
Bandaji with no interior fitments were used for clothes and bedding in the female quarters, </segment>
    <segment id="17" parent="16" relname="elaboration">

as was the Museum&apos;s mid-nineteenth-century example.</segment>
    <segment id="18" parent="19" relname="span">
It is made of zelkova, 
a hardwood of the elm family, </segment>
    <segment id="20" parent="18" relname="elaboration">
and its fine colour and grain are exploited to the full.  </segment>
    <segment id="21" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
The brass fitments on chests often expressed good luck, long life and happiness, particularly as the chests were commonly wedding gifts or part of a dowry.  </segment>
    <segment id="22" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
Hinges at the base of the upper half of the chest are shaped as two spools, representing longevity, </segment>
    <segment id="23" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
and at the centre is a hinge in the shape of a medicine bottle for good health.  </segment>
    <segment id="24" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
The characters in the lower half stand for double happiness, </segment>
    <segment id="25" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
and the bat is a symbol of good luck.  </segment>
    <segment id="26" parent="16" relname="elaboration">
The brass bosses are said to represent the big dipper, another symbol of longevity.</segment>
    <segment id="27" parent="16" relname="elaboration"> 
The chest is made of planks of wood joined at top and sides with finger jointing.  </segment>
    <segment id="28" parent="37" relname="span">
The brass hinges and splice plates strengthen the joins and add to the distinctive style of the chest, </segment>
    <segment id="29" parent="28" relname="interpretation">
placing its manufacture in the Kyoung-gi-do area around Seoul.</segment>
